To conclude, we have demonstrated that the presence of partially wettable particles on the walls can dramatically affect the dynamics of a liquid finger that is injected into a Hele-Shaw cell filled with air.  Generally, a fingering pattern forms, even though the displacement of air with a viscous fluid is typically stable, unlike the classical Saffman-Taylor instability. The destabilization of the interface occurs due to interfacial energy minimization, which requires that all particles intersected by the meniscus are collected. As a consequence, the critical radius at which the instability occurs and the width of the fingers can be calculated by simply balancing the space available on the meniscus with the area needed to accomodate additional particles encountered by the liquid-air interface during its motion.


